args: Ilia teaches that love tolerates all things,\nis compassionate, never grows envious...
...endures all things, believes in all\nthings, hopes for all things...
Everyone in the village rejoiced in\nreceiving the word of Ilia.
Not at all. I am a preacher; it is the least\nthat I could do.
We look forward to your next sermon.
I'm glad to hear that. I am still studying,\nbut I hope my passion will make up for\nmy inexperience.
I sure was. The villagers were hanging\non your every word!
Still, you must think I'm not really cut out\nfor this kind of work...
Not at all. Though it is a side of you\nI'm not really used to seeing.
That's nice, but I have a long way to go\nuntil I reach the level I want to be at.
Well, the reason I wanted to become a\npreacher was because that's what my\ngrandmother did.
When I was little, I was always getting\ninto trouble.
Really? Heh. I never would've guessed,\nbut I can kind of see it...
My grandmother was the kindest woman\nI'd ever met.
She hardly ever scolded me for being such\na mischief-maker.
...Until the day I pulled a truly awful prank.
Oh. What did your grandmother do?
She disciplined meâ€”for the first time\nin my life.
Let me guess: the Loving Hand?
Yes. I remember it as if it were\nyesterday...
Er, but I thought the point of the Loving\nHand was that it DOESN'T hurt.
The pain I felt was not physical.
It was an ache deep in my chest.
The very same anguish that I had inflicted\non my grandmother.
So the Loving Hand conveys the pain in a\nperson's heart?

Exactly! The Loving Hand is not supposed
to hurt; rather, it is supposed to make
someone understand the emotional pain
that YOU feel.
Seeing you talk about your grandmother\nwith such love makes me understand\nhow wonderful she was.
Why? There's nothing to be embarrassed\nabout.
No, it's just... I have a bad habit of letting\nmy emotions get the better of me.
I rely on the Loving Hand far too much.
But that's not a bad thing, is it?
It is unacceptable behavior for a preacher\nto engage in, Loving Hand or no.
I ought to be kind and compassionate,\nnot let my temper get the better of me!
Well, that may be the right thing to do\nas a preacher...
But I like you just the way you are.\nI know you're trying the best you can.
Augh! I'm so sorry! See, I just do it\nwithout thinking!
Ha ha! That's okay. It's just who you are.
And everyone loves you for who you are.
Y-you... You really are a villain!
